article.description: Latrell Sprewell and Kurt Thomas each stole the ball from Yao on two late possessions as the New York Knicks snapped a four-game losing streak with a 102-95 victory over the Houston Rockets.
article.headline: Knicks end four-game skid, impressed by Yao
article.linkText: Knicks get best of Yao at end to break slide
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) --Forget about the 24 points, the six rebounds, the deft footwork and the adoring cheers. The thing that made the biggest difference Tuesday night was Yao Ming's five turnovers. Latrell Sprewell and Kurt Thomas each stole the ball from Yao on two late possessions as the New York Knicks snapped a four-game losing streak with a 102-95 victory over the Houston Rockets. Yao had an otherwise fine performance in his first appearance at Madison Square Garden, but his two turnovers down the stretch were costly. "He had a great game, shot the ball well, rebounded,'' Thomas said. "He did everything Houston could have asked from him, but we were able to limit him a little and were able to come away with the win.'' Allan Houston scored 28, Shandon Anderson had 14 and Sprewell and Thomas added 13 apiece for the Knicks, who scored eight of the game's final nine points. Clarence Weatherspoon also made a big contribution with nine points and three rebounds in the fourth quarter. "It was huge for our team. This was a game we talked about -- having to break the four-game losing streak,'' Sprewell said. Cuttino Mobley scored 25 and Steve Francis added 19 for Houston, which had its two-game winning streak snapped. The Rockets were coming off an overtime victory at Boston the previous night, and their fatigue was noticeable. The Knicks capitalized by coming up with several key defensive plays in the fourth. Howard Eisley stole the ball from Mobley before hitting a 3 with 2:44 remaining to give the Knicks their first lead of the fourth quarter, 91-89. Yao answered with a three-point play, executing a nifty drop step move around Weatherspoon for a dunk. After a missed 3 by Eisley, the Rockets tried to run the same play -- but Sprewell sneaked inside and swatted the ball away before pulling up for a 3-pointer that gave New York a 94-92 lead with 1:50 left. "Once I got the steal, guys were playing off me, and I told myself this was do-or-die and I'm going to live with the results on this one. So I just let it go,'' Sprewell said. Yao answered with a short jumper, but he didn't leave his feet at the other end to try to block Weatherspoon's 4-footer that gave New York the lead for good. Thomas had his most significant defensive play of the night on the next possession, deflecting the ball away from Yao in the low post. It led to a 14-footer by Sprewell for a four-point lead. "I wasn't tired. I just turned over the ball,'' Yao said through an interpreter. Francis was then called for an offensive foul, and Thomas locked up the victory on a corner jumper with 25.9 seconds left for a 100-94 lead.

Game notes
The Knicks played the final game in a stretch of 11 straight against teams from the Western Conference. ... Yao was bothered by a sore left elbow, but it did not keep him out of the game. ... Knicks rookie G Frank Williams played eight minutes on his 23 birthday, making his only shot and committing three fouls. ... Houston, the league's leading free throw shooter, missed one with 3:39 left.
